<subSubSection id="C33508E2B600FF8AFC71FBBAFBEAF960" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8B905B69B600FF8AFC71FBBAFB6FFB92" blockId="7.[1012,1257,1105,1129]" box="[1012,1257,1105,1129]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
<heading id="D0D8EC05B600FF8AFC71FBBAFB6FFB92" box="[1012,1257,1105,1129]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" reason="2">
THE 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFBA9FBBEFB6FFB92" authority="ISSUE" box="[1068,1257,1109,1128]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFBA9FBBEFB19FB92" box="[1068,1183,1109,1128]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">ERESIMUS</emphasis>
ISSUE
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B905B69B600FF8AFCBFFB91FBEAF960" blockId="7.[826,1442,1146,1904]" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
The taxon 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFC43FB90FBACFB6A" box="[966,1066,1147,1168]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFC43FB90FBACFB6A" box="[966,1066,1147,1168]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">eresimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFBDDFB91FB3FFB75" box="[1112,1209,1146,1167]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexaure">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFBDDFB91FB3FFB75" box="[1112,1209,1146,1167]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexaure</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFCBFFB72FC10FB54" baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[826,918,1177,1198]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFCBFFB72FC10FB54" box="[826,918,1177,1198]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">gilippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
over 95% of their very extensive combined range, from Texas and 
<collectingRegion id="49EB958BB600FF8AFBBFFB53FB0BFB34" box="[1082,1165,1208,1230]" country="Uruguay" name="Florida" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Florida</collectingRegion>
in the north to 
<collectingCountry id="F3381BF9B600FF8AFABEFB53FA24FB37" box="[1339,1442,1208,1229]" name="Uruguay" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F3381BF9B600FF8AFCF4FB3DFC63FB16" box="[881,997,1238,1260]" name="Argentina" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Argentina</collectingCountry>
in the south. Where these two very similar species fly together, the feature that serves best to distinguish them on the wing is a series of pale patches (character 54, Appendix 1A, B) on the hindwing underside of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB89FAB9FBF6FA9D" box="[1036,1136,1362,1383]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB89FAB9FBF6FA9D" box="[1036,1136,1362,1383]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">eresimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB0EFABAFB6AFA9C" box="[1163,1260,1361,1382]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexaure">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB0EFABAFB6AFA9C" box="[1163,1260,1361,1382]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexaure</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This character, unique within 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFC68FA9BFBC0FA7F" authorityName="Kluk" authorityYear="1802" box="[1005,1094,1392,1413]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFC68FA9BFBC0FA7F" box="[1005,1094,1392,1413]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Danaus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, may aid species recognition and, thus, mate selection in sympatry. Because butterfly eyes are sensitive both to ultraviolet (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFA8FFA46FC41FA18" author="Silberglied RE &amp; Taylor OR" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="203 - 243" refId="ref16829" refString="Silberglied RE, Taylor OR. 1978. Ultraviolet reflection and its behavioural role in the courtship of the sulphur butterflies, Colias eurytheme and C. philodice. Behavioural Ecology and Sociobiology 3: 203 - 243." type="journal article" year="1978">Silberglied &amp; Taylor, 1978</bibRefCitation>
) and polarized light (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B600FF8AFB47FA27FC59F9FA" author="Sweeney A &amp; Jiggins C &amp; Johnsen S" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" pagination="31 - 32" refId="ref17319" refString="Sweeney A, Jiggins C, Johnsen S. 2003. Polarized light as a butterfly mating signal. Nature 423: 31 - 32." type="journal article" year="2003">Sweeney, Jiggins &amp; Johnsen, 2003</bibRefCitation>
) an investigation of the optical properties of these patches could be rewarding. Even to the human eye, the patches serve equally well to distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFC04F9ADFC64F9A1" box="[897,994,1606,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexaure">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFC04F9ADFC64F9A1" box="[897,994,1606,1627]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">plexaure</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFBADF9ADFB6EF9A1" baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[1064,1256,1606,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFBADF9ADFB6EF9A1" box="[1064,1256,1606,1627]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">gilippus gilippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F3381BF9B600FF8AFA8AF9ADFA05F9A6" box="[1295,1411,1606,1628]" name="Argentina" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Argentina</collectingCountry>
or 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFCBFF98DFC6FF980" box="[826,1001,1637,1659]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFCBFF98DFC18F981" box="[826,926,1638,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">eresimus</taxonomicName>
tethys
</emphasis>
from 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFBAAF98EFB76F980" box="[1071,1264,1637,1658]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFBAAF98EFB0DF980" baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[1071,1163,1637,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilippus">gilippus</taxonomicName>
berenice
</emphasis>
on Grand Cayman (DASS, unpublished).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33508E2B600FF85FCD6F949FF63FD3E" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="199" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B905B69B600FF85FCD6F949FF63FD3E" blockId="7.[826,1442,1146,1904]" lastBlockId="8.[142,758,196,708]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="199" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">
The phylogenetic tree derived from mtDNA data (
<figureCitation id="131447ECB600FF8AFCC7F92AFC13F92D" box="[834,917,1729,1751]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[165,243,1414,1433]" captionTargetBox="[331,1276,204,1382]" captionTargetId="graphics-415@4.[334,1069,703,1096]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. A, single most parsimonious tree based on amalgamated mtDNA 12S rRNA (344 bp†) and COI (676 bp†) genes (Appendix 2) for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups Tirumala septentrionis and T. limniace (†values before alignment). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 1025, variable informative characters 54, parsimony informative characters 139, heuristic search length 304, consistency index (CI) = 0.80, homoplasy index (HI) = 0.20, retention index (RI) = 0.81, rescaled consistency index (RCI) = 0.65. Bootstrap replicates/Bremer Support values are shown for each node where significant. Branch lengths are drawn proportional to nucleotide changes and indicated in parentheses. The MP topology depicted here is congruent with the MP strict consensus, NJ and ML algorithms not shown. ML branch significance is P &lt;0.01 unless marked *. See Table 1 for provenances and sample sizes. B, single most parsimonious tree based on morphological, biochemical and colour gene characters (Appendix 1A, B) for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups T. septentrionis and T. limniace (characters from T. petiverana, T. hamata and T. ishmoides were used to fill gaps); †character alignment was fixed to character). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 67†, variable uninformative characters 8, parsimony informative characters 59, heuristic search length 95, CI = 0.84, HI = 0.16, RI = 0.90, RCI = 0.75. Other notes as in (A). C, one of 11 most parsimonious trees based on amalgamated nDNA 18S rRNA (525 bp†) and EF1-a (400 bp†) genes for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups Amauris niavius and A. ellioti (†values before alignment). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 926, variable uninformative characters 19, parsimony informative characters 24, heuristic search length 52, CI = 0.83, HI = 0.17, RI = 0.72, RCI = 0.60. Other notes as in (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434144" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434144/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
) places the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB99F92AFB10F92C" authorityName="Smith &amp; Lushai &amp; Allen" authorityYear="2005" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1052,1174,1729,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB99F92AFB10F92C" box="[1052,1174,1729,1750]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">chrysippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB34F92AFB7CF92C" authorityName="Lushai et al." authorityYear="2005" baseAuthorityName="Stoll" baseAuthorityYear="1790" box="[1201,1274,1729,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petilia">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB34F92AFB7CF92C" box="[1201,1274,1729,1750]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">petilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade as sister to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFCD2F90BFC3DF90F" box="[855,955,1760,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFCD2F90BFC3DF90F" box="[855,955,1760,1781]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">eresimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFC53F90BFBB4F90F" baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[982,1074,1760,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFC53F90BFBB4F90F" box="[982,1074,1760,1781]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">gilippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; with the proviso that 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFAB0F90BFCCEF8E9" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">dorippus- 1</emphasis>
is excluded from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB94F914FBD9F8EE" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1816" box="[1041,1119,1791,1812]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Anosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB94F914FBD9F8EE" box="[1041,1119,1791,1812]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Anosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the remaining species form a monophyletic group. The 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB18F8F6FB6DF8C8" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1816" box="[1181,1259,1821,1842]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Anosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB18F8F6FB6DF8C8" box="[1181,1259,1821,1842]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Anosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cluster, again excluding 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFC38F8D7FBBEF8AB" box="[957,1080,1852,1873]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">dorippus-1</emphasis>
, is sister to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB79F8D7FAE4F8AB" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1880" box="[1276,1378,1852,1873]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Salatura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB79F8D7FAE4F8AB" box="[1276,1378,1852,1873]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Salatura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFCBFF8B1FC26F895" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1880" box="[826,928,1882,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Salatura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFCBFF8B1FC26F895" box="[826,928,1882,1903]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Salatura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFC39F8B0FB8CF88A" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1816" box="[956,1034,1883,1904]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Anosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFC39F8B0FB8CF88A" box="[956,1034,1883,1904]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Anosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB600FF8AFB15F8B0FB6FF88A" authorityName="Kluk" authorityYear="1802" box="[1168,1257,1883,1904]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="198" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB600FF8AFB15F8B0FB6FF88A" box="[1168,1257,1883,1904]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="198">Danaus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Comparing the topology derived from mtDNA characters (
<figureCitation id="131447ECB60FFF85FD19FF2FFD69FF20" box="[668,751,196,218]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[165,243,1414,1433]" captionTargetBox="[331,1276,204,1382]" captionTargetId="graphics-415@4.[334,1069,703,1096]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. A, single most parsimonious tree based on amalgamated mtDNA 12S rRNA (344 bp†) and COI (676 bp†) genes (Appendix 2) for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups Tirumala septentrionis and T. limniace (†values before alignment). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 1025, variable informative characters 54, parsimony informative characters 139, heuristic search length 304, consistency index (CI) = 0.80, homoplasy index (HI) = 0.20, retention index (RI) = 0.81, rescaled consistency index (RCI) = 0.65. Bootstrap replicates/Bremer Support values are shown for each node where significant. Branch lengths are drawn proportional to nucleotide changes and indicated in parentheses. The MP topology depicted here is congruent with the MP strict consensus, NJ and ML algorithms not shown. ML branch significance is P &lt;0.01 unless marked *. See Table 1 for provenances and sample sizes. B, single most parsimonious tree based on morphological, biochemical and colour gene characters (Appendix 1A, B) for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups T. septentrionis and T. limniace (characters from T. petiverana, T. hamata and T. ishmoides were used to fill gaps); †character alignment was fixed to character). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 67†, variable uninformative characters 8, parsimony informative characters 59, heuristic search length 95, CI = 0.84, HI = 0.16, RI = 0.90, RCI = 0.75. Other notes as in (A). C, one of 11 most parsimonious trees based on amalgamated nDNA 18S rRNA (525 bp†) and EF1-a (400 bp†) genes for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups Amauris niavius and A. ellioti (†values before alignment). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 926, variable uninformative characters 19, parsimony informative characters 24, heuristic search length 52, CI = 0.83, HI = 0.17, RI = 0.72, RCI = 0.60. Other notes as in (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434144" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434144/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
) with that based on morphological characters (
<figureCitation id="131447ECB60FFF85FF13FEEAFF6FFEED" box="[150,233,257,279]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="4.[165,243,1414,1433]" captionTargetBox="[331,1276,204,1382]" captionTargetId="graphics-415@4.[334,1069,703,1096]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 2. A, single most parsimonious tree based on amalgamated mtDNA 12S rRNA (344 bp†) and COI (676 bp†) genes (Appendix 2) for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups Tirumala septentrionis and T. limniace (†values before alignment). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 1025, variable informative characters 54, parsimony informative characters 139, heuristic search length 304, consistency index (CI) = 0.80, homoplasy index (HI) = 0.20, retention index (RI) = 0.81, rescaled consistency index (RCI) = 0.65. Bootstrap replicates/Bremer Support values are shown for each node where significant. Branch lengths are drawn proportional to nucleotide changes and indicated in parentheses. The MP topology depicted here is congruent with the MP strict consensus, NJ and ML algorithms not shown. ML branch significance is P &lt;0.01 unless marked *. See Table 1 for provenances and sample sizes. B, single most parsimonious tree based on morphological, biochemical and colour gene characters (Appendix 1A, B) for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups T. septentrionis and T. limniace (characters from T. petiverana, T. hamata and T. ishmoides were used to fill gaps); †character alignment was fixed to character). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 67†, variable uninformative characters 8, parsimony informative characters 59, heuristic search length 95, CI = 0.84, HI = 0.16, RI = 0.90, RCI = 0.75. Other notes as in (A). C, one of 11 most parsimonious trees based on amalgamated nDNA 18S rRNA (525 bp†) and EF1-a (400 bp†) genes for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups Amauris niavius and A. ellioti (†values before alignment). Tree statistics: characters in matrix 926, variable uninformative characters 19, parsimony informative characters 24, heuristic search length 52, CI = 0.83, HI = 0.17, RI = 0.72, RCI = 0.60. Other notes as in (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434144" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434144/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
), it is clear that the relationships found for 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FF0BFECBFF74FECF" box="[142,242,288,309]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FF0BFECBFF74FECF" box="[142,242,288,309]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">eresimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are discordant. Whereas the mitochondrial genomes of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FE9DFED4FEFAFEAE" box="[280,380,319,340]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FE9DFED4FEFAFEAE" box="[280,380,319,340]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">eresimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FE3EFED5FD91FEA9" baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[443,535,318,339]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FE3EFED5FD91FEA9" box="[443,535,318,339]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">gilippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are virtually identical (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBE2698B60FFF85FF56FEB6FE39FE89" author="Lushai G &amp; Smith DAS &amp; Gordon IJ &amp; Goulson D &amp; Allen JA &amp; Maclean N" box="[211,447,349,371]" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" pagination="236 - 246" refId="ref16222" refString="Lushai G, Smith DAS, Gordon IJ, Goulson D, Allen JA, Maclean N. 2003 a. Incomplete sexual isolation in sympatry between subspecies of the butterfly Danaus chrysippus (L.) and the creation of a hybrid zone. Heredity 90: 236 - 246." type="journal article" year="2003">
Lushai 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FEAAFEB5FEE6FE88" box="[303,352,349,371]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">et al</emphasis>
., 2003a
</bibRefCitation>
), and the two New World species share a sister relationship with the Old World 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FF0BFE70FEB3FE4A" box="[142,309,410,432]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Anosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FF0BFE70FF5AFE4A" box="[142,220,411,432]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">Anosia</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, the nuclear data suggest otherwise. In the latter case, with the substantial caveat that the relevant nodes have weak support, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FDACFE33FD0BFE17" box="[553,653,472,493]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FDACFE33FD0BFE17" box="[553,653,472,493]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">eresimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not cluster with 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FE9AFE1CFEEBFDF6" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1816" box="[287,365,503,524]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Anosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FE9AFE1CFEEBFDF6" box="[287,365,503,524]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">Anosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but rather with 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FDB3FE1DFD24FDF1" baseAuthorityName="LINNAEUS" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[566,674,502,523]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plexippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FDB3FE1DFD24FDF1" box="[566,674,502,523]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">plexippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FD44FE1CFF30FDD1" class="Insecta" family="Papilionidae" genus="Papilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FD44FE1CFF30FDD1" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">erippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The analysis of total evidence (
<figureCitation id="131447ECB60FFF85FDC4FDFEFD06FDD1" box="[577,640,533,555]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[162,240,585,604]" captionText="Figure 3. Single most parsimonious tree based on total evidence (amalgamated characters from Fig. 2) for the genus Danaus, rooted by outgroups T. septentrionis and T. limniace. Tree statistics: characters in matrix 2024, variable informative characters 76, parsimony informative characters 209, heuristic search length 445, CI = 0.79, HI = 0.21, RI = 0.80, RCI = 0.64. 1000 Bootstrap replicates/Bremer Support values are shown for each node where significant branch lengths are indicated in parentheses. This is the parsimony strict consensus tree and is congruent with trees from NJ and ML algorithms, not shown. ML branch significance is P &lt;0.01 unless marked *." pageId="8" pageNumber="199">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) provides strong support for the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FE1FFDDFFE78FDB3" box="[410,510,564,585]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eresimus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FE1FFDDFFE78FDB3" box="[410,510,564,585]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">eresimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FD9AFDDFFDFDFDB3" baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[543,635,564,585]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilippus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FD9AFDDFFDFDFDB3" box="[543,635,564,585]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">gilippus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade, but not for its inclusion in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FE25FDB8FE68FD92" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1816" box="[416,494,595,616]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Anosia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FE25FDB8FE68FD92" box="[416,494,595,616]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">Anosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, nor indeed any other subgenus. These anomalies strengthen the case for abandoning the A &amp; V-W subgenera of 
<emphasis id="B95B877BB60FFF85FDF4FD7BFD70FD5F" box="[625,758,656,677]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">
<taxonomicName id="4C2F20EAB60FFF85FDF4FD7BFD4CFD5F" authorityName="Kluk" authorityYear="1802" box="[625,714,656,677]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Danaus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">Danaus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2683A00B60FFF85FD53FD7BFD70FD5F" box="[726,758,656,677]" pageId="8" pageNumber="199" sensu="lato">s.l.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131447ECB60FFF85FF13FD45FF53FD3E" box="[150,213,686,708]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="1.[826,904,663,682]" captionTargetBox="[830,1437,233,630]" captionTargetId="graphics-739@1.[900,1344,240,621]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figure 1. Cladistic reconstruction of the genus Danaus, after Ackery &amp; Vane-Wright (1984)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5434142" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5434142/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="199">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
